The refactored code separates the responsibilities of the `MusicPlayer` interface into multiple smaller interfaces, such as `Playable`, `TrackSkippable`, `Ejectable`, etc. This adheres to the Single Responsibility Principle and the Interface Segregation Principle, allowing each player type to implement only the methods that are relevant to them. The `Amplifier` class no longer implements methods that are not applicable, thus fulfilling the Liskov Substitution Principle. This design also allows for easier extension of the system in the future.

